
@startuml

' Define classes and their attributes

class Song {
  +String title
  +int year
  +float length
  +String genre
}

class Artist {
  +String name (PK)
  +Date dob
  +String url
}

class User {
  +String id (PK)
  +String name
  +String address
}

class BusinessUser {
  +String vatNumber
}

class RegularUser {
}

class Album {
  +String title
  +int trackNumber
}

class Single {
}

class Hit {
}

' Inheritance relationships

User <|-- BusinessUser
User <|-- RegularUser

Song <|-- Single
Song <|-- Hit

Album "1" --> "many" Hit : contains
Hit "1" --> "1" Album : part of

Artist "1" --> "many" Song : creates
Song "1" --> "1" Artist : belongs to
Song "1" --> "1" User : uploaded by
BusinessUser "1" --> "many" Song : uploads

RegularUser "1" --> "many" Single : buys
RegularUser "1" --> "many" Album : owns

' Associations with notes

note right of Album
  An album consists only of hits.
  Each hit has a track number in the album.
end note

note right of Single
  Singles can be directly purchased by regular users.
end note

note right of Hit
  Hits can be part of an album.
end note

note right of RegularUser
  Can be both a buyer (regular user) and a seller (business user).
end note

@enduml

---

### ✅ Explanation of Key Points:

- **Song** is a base class for `Single` and `Hit`.
- **Artist** is uniquely identified by name and is associated with one or more songs.
- **User** is a base class for `RegularUser` and `BusinessUser`, allowing a person to act in both roles.
- **Album** contains multiple `Hit`s, each with a unique `trackNumber`.
- **RegularUser** can purchase singles or albums.
- **BusinessUser** uploads songs (`Single` or `Hit`) but not albums.

This class diagram captures all the required entities and their relationships according to the system specification.